The boundary has to be determined by the seeker himself/herself, or i=
f he/she has a Guru who has accomplished the full sadhana of that specific =
path, or an uttara-sadhaka (a more advanced sadhaka). All fixed rules are b=
ased on circumstances when the rules are set. From time to time the rules n=
eed to be modified, added, or subtracted or improvised based on current sit=
uations.

Let me give you an example. There are some people here who do Cha=
ndipath and Chandi homas. Now the historically, the Sri Sri Chandi is a Tan=
tric text which was the mainstay on Kali-Kula Tantric Paramparas for ages. =
Maximum worship, and siddhis of Sri Sri Chandi sadhana has happened from pa=
ramparas originating and centering around the Kamakhya Shakti Peetha. These=
 paramparas had fantastic Gurus, some of whom were really Mahasiddhas. If y=
ou follow the texts from these paramparas, which are very ancient, one shou=
ld not even touch the book of Sri Sri Chandi until one has been given a gen=
uine Shaktipath diksha by a competent Guru. First there is a Shakta Abhisek=
h, then=C2=A0 once a certain level is reached a PurnaAbhisekh, and in some =
rare cases a BhairavaAbhisekh. Moreover, the Tantras are clear that to achi=
eve the grace of Sri Sri Chandi a sadhaka must stay completely alone and do=
 the sadhana in a deserted shiva-temple, or inside a forest where humans do=
 not
 enter, on a hill-top where people do not live, near a river bank unde=
r certain specific trees where there is no habitation nearby , or a smashan=
 which is away from the city. These were the original instructions and whoe=
ver did not follow the same can, it was said, fall in serious trouble inclu=
ding but not limited to death. But over time, many other people have done s=
adhana of Sri Sri Chandi, often not following all the laid down rules or im=
provising on them, and yet achieved various degrees of high **realizations.=
 So rules need to understood first, and the reinterpreted based on circumst=
ances.

Similarly for everything there are many rules laid out at various p=
oints of time by great masters, which are at times even contradictory, and =
they have a deeper reason too. But if you can figure out the reason behind =
the rules, or someone helps you to figure out the reason, then you can very=
 well improvise based on your current situation. At any cost, it is good an=
d nice to have some joy in your sadhana by maintaining a right balance betw=
een being too strict on rules vs following what thoughts come naturally to =
aid your sadhana.


The word meditation in English really covers two differ=
ent concepts. a) Concentration. b) Contemplation.

For concentration you si=
t in an asana and fix your thoughts on something, be it a mantra or a deity=
 ETC. This need 
a still body and then a still mind. First the mind will be=
come calm. Then eventually the mind will become quite. In a normal human mi=
nd there is a constant running commentary going on. That needs to be stoppe=
d eventually. When that is done, without or without a mantra, various kinds=
 of interesting experiences come to the seeker. But the problem with this m=
ethod is that, its gains are often limited to only the time frame when you =
are stilling and concentrating. Once you go back to teh world, your gains a=
re either lost or frittered away. It takes a really long time to get such a=
 one-off experience in focused concentration which is powerful enough to ch=
ange your surface personality even during other times. For most seekers, su=
ch a thing never happens. 

Contemplation is when you keep your focus on a =
mantra or a deity even with engaging in all kinds of activities. This is a =
process of knowing by becoming. If you keep contemplating constantly for da=
ys on end on one specific things, you will often gain some knowlege/underst=
anding about it by way of association. This is a very useful sadhana. Unlik=
e concentration, this can be and is ment to be done even while doing all ot=
her things. 

When you do both, that is focused concentration while keeping=
 the body still, and contemplation of Divine at all points even when engage=
d in other activities, then a dual effect accrues in your system which has =
a greater chance of changing your surface daily personality. For all sadhan=
a eventually must do just that.


**realization, the English word, is super=
 vague. In spirituality, if one does an objective reckoning of scriptures, =
paths, sadhanas, and experiences of various legendary sadhakas one will see=
 that there are vast multidimensional number and nature of great spiritual =
realizations. And they are not similar at all. It is a complex and interest=
ing study in itself. The proverbial reality is One, but it is so complex th=
at few, even among greats, have ever had a complete realization of all aspe=
cts of the One. 

-Regards
